50|$|In 1933 The Indian Express {{opened its}} second office in Madurai, {{launching}} the Tamil edition, Dinamani. Sadanand introduced several innovations {{and reduced the}} price of the newspaper. Faced with financial difficulties, he sold a part of his stake to Ramanath Goenka as <b>convertible</b> <b>debentures.</b> In 1935, when The Free Press Journal finally collapsed, and after a protracted court battle with Goenka, Sadanand lost ownership of Indian Express.|$|E
